&lt;p&gt;If management ainâ€™t Agile, ainâ€™t no one Agile.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span id=&#34;more&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;Really-Do-you-know-what-youâ€™re-saying&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Really-Do-you-know-what-youâ€™re-saying&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Really?Â  Do you know what youâ€™re saying?!&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Really?Â  Do you know what youâ€™re saying?!&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Many people even use the words â€œAgileâ€ and â€œScrumâ€ interchangeably.Â  Most because they really do think they are the same thing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Iâ€™m finding that what most people mean when they use these words is, either, â€œwe work really fastâ€, â€œwe work iterativelyâ€, or â€œwe donâ€™t really have a plan.â€&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;So-the-first-thing-we-need-to-clarify-is-what-is-Scrum-and-what-is-Agile&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#So-the-first-thing-we-need-to-clarify-is-what-is-Scrum-and-what-is-Agile&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;So, the first thing we need to clarify is, what is Scrum and what is Agile.&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;So, the first thing we need to clarify is, what is Scrum and what is Agile.&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Agile is a set of values.Â  It is what we believe about software development specifically and, I would argue, also impacts how we view life.Â  You might have other beliefs that live on top of Agile, but these beliefs will have an impact on how you manage the software development process specifically and your organization in general. Check out the &lt;a href=&#34;//www.agilemanifesto.org/&#34;&gt;Agile Manifesto&lt;/a&gt;.Â  This is what it means to be Agile.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In contrast to this, Scrum is a methodology that helps an organization BE agile.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now here is where things get tricky for some people.Â  They read in the manifesto that we should value â€œIndividuals and interactions over processes and toolsâ€ and think that they can make Scrum be whatever they want it to be because, they would say, â€œwe donâ€™t value processes and toolsâ€.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But the Agile Manifesto never says that.Â  It says we value individuals and interactions MORE than, not INSTEAD of, processes and tools.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, yes, you can adapt and modify Scrum to fit your situation.Â  You may need to.Â  But there are some specific elements of Scrum that you simply canâ€™t ignore because to do so would mean either that you are no longer Agile or you are not implementing Scrum.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;And-so-you-arenâ€™t-doing-Scrum-if&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#And-so-you-arenâ€™t-doing-Scrum-if&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;And so, you arenâ€™t doing Scrum if:&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;And so, you arenâ€™t doing Scrum if:&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;h4 id=&#34;You-have-deadlines-especially-if-you-have-â€œtight-deadlinesâ€&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#You-have-deadlines-especially-if-you-have-â€œtight-deadlinesâ€&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;You have deadlines, especially if you have â€œtight deadlinesâ€&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;You have deadlines, especially if you have â€œtight deadlinesâ€&lt;/h4&gt;&lt;p&gt;â€œNow wait a minute,â€ you say, â€œI heard that Scrum has these things called â€˜Sprintsâ€™ that are a fixed length.Â  Donâ€™t those qualify as â€˜deadlines?â€™â€ Well, yes and no.Â  You see, I donâ€™t think what Scrum treats as a â€œdeadlineâ€ is what most managers mean by â€œdeadline.â€ At the end of the day youâ€™ll get to the end of the Sprint and youâ€™ll show what youâ€™ve got.Â  The GOAL is to have a complete set of code that you wouldnâ€™t be embarrassed to show to another programmer.Â  You should have only selected what could reasonably get done in the timeframe of a sprint so that all that needs to be done to complete the task could get done.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One of the confusions is that somewhere along the line we were told that at the end of each sprint we should have a â€œshippable unit of softwareâ€ and weâ€™ve confused that with â€œa viably marketable productâ€Â  All that shippable means is, â€œif the customer thinks what youâ€™ve completed so far is something they can use, you would not respond with, â€˜but it still needsâ€¦â€™â€ This ties in with the other way you know you arenâ€™t doing Scrum&lt;/p&gt;
