&lt;p&gt;In summary, we can have multiple classes and new them up.Â  Or we can have one class with multiple static methods that return object literals.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Advantage-Object-Literal&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Advantage-Object-Literal&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Advantage Object Literal&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Advantage Object Literal&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;The main advantage to using the object literal way is that you donâ€™t need to create an object.Â  You also stay with the â€œOne class, one fileâ€ model that is so common in Angular. On the surface, this seems to be a clear winner.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Advantage-Classes&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Advantage-Classes&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Advantage Classes&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Advantage Classes&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;But, because of the way we import the class bundles, the way we end up using the code looks nearly the same.Â  The main difference is that we must instantiate the class.Â  But we also get the option of having a different variable type for each action, we arenâ€™t forced to use a variable named â€œpayloadâ€ to hold all the associated data.Â  Further, if you need multiple payloads, you can do that.Â  You arenâ€™t limited by how many parameters&amp;#x2F;member variables each of your Action classes use.Â  When using Effects, we can type the return value of the Effect to the Action we want it to return. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In fact, it is this type safety that is the main reason we should be creating Actions using the Class method instead of the object literal method.&lt;/p&gt;
