&lt;h2 id=&#34;What-Is-Clarity&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#What-Is-Clarity&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;What Is Clarity?&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;What Is Clarity?&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;To call it a CSS Framework though doesnâ€™t really do it justice.Â  It is a UI&amp;#x2F;UX System.Â  Much like Angular Material.Â  In fact, an application written using Clarity is going to end up looking a lot like a Material Design application.Â  The main differences are going to be, it will be built for the desktop rather than a mobile device.Â  This means the components wonâ€™t be so fat and the components will look more like what you would expect from a desktop application.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Why-Clarity&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Why-Clarity&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Why Clarity?&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Why Clarity?&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Aside from the Desktop vs Mobile issue, there are other reasons you might want to consider using Clarity.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;Material-Meets-Bootstrap&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Material-Meets-Bootstrap&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Material Meets Bootstrap&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Material Meets Bootstrap&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now, while the end result looks a lot like Angular Material, the way you style your application feels a lot more like Bootstrap.Â  This is something that has always bothered me about Angular Material.Â  In fact, one of the main reasons we didnâ€™t use Angular Material at one of the places Iâ€™ve worked is specifically because it was too hard to make the site follow the design guides that were handed down to us.Â  Bootstrap, on the other hand, gave us an easy way to adapt the CSS to fit the requirements.Â  Give me components that provide functionality and provide a way that I can style them.Â  But donâ€™t make common components their own special component just so you can add CSS to the standard element.Â  Make that a common CSS thing that you can change with CSS!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;508-Compliance&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#508-Compliance&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;508 Compliance&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;508 Compliance&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Another big motivation for me to look at Clarity is that they have stricter 508 compliance if you use the default theme.Â  The one that is particularly important to me is the issue of contrast to support people who are color blind like me.Â  Thatâ€™s 10% of the population that is impacted by color blindness in general which is a pretty large sample size to be pissing off with your color choices when there are tools that will let you see what it will look like to the various type of color blind people.Â  There compliance doesnâ€™t end there, but that is the one that impacts me, so I care more about it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;More-x2F-Better-Components&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#More-x2F-Better-Components&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;More&amp;#x2F;Better Components&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;More&amp;#x2F;Better Components&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Third, several components exist that meet some requirements that the team Iâ€™m currently working on could have benefited from. While Angular Material is moving to fill in some of the gaps, the Clarity system has those components already.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;Great-Documentation&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Great-Documentation&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Great Documentation&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Great Documentation&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;While it isnâ€™t necessarily unique to Clarity, I found the documentation complete and easy to locate.Â  However, just like any of the other systems, you should take the time to read through most of the documentation, so you understand how it should work prior to actually trying to code anything.&lt;/p&gt;
