&lt;p&gt;Funny story.Â  A couple of gigs ago, a manager from three levels up came down to visit after I had left for the day.Â  She looked at my desk and said, â€œDoes anyone work here?â€Â  My manager said, â€œYES!!! Donâ€™t touch anything!â€Â  Guess she was hunting for stray equipment. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I would say, this simple act was the pivot point for me when I started to care more about my code beyond â€œDoes it work?â€ &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is something about working in a clean area slightly dressed up.Â  Other parts of your life follow along for the ride.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Linters&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Linters&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Linters&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Linters&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;One of those areas is what your code looks like.Â  A linter can be configured to enforce style rules on your code.Â  And can also catch dumb mistakes.Â  The more I use linters, the more convinced I am everyone should use one. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here is some of the ways you will benefit, even if you are the only one using a linter.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Your code will always follow the same format.Â  This will make the code easier to read and understand.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;As I mentioned, some rules help catch dumb mistakes before you even run the code.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Just like a clean desk feels inviting, well formatted code feels inviting.Â  The converse, poorly formatted code, adds to the stress level of working on the code.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Learn-Your-Tools&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Learn-Your-Tools&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Learn Your Tools&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Learn Your Tools&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;I am amazed at how many places Iâ€™ve worked where they expect you to learn a particular tool on the fly.Â  No training.Â  â€œWe are now using X on this next project.Â  Download it and start using it!â€Â  And then they wonder why the project is such a disaster.Â  Bugs everywhere. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Want to look like a rock star?Â  Want to be the guy the boss ask â€œwhat should we do?â€Â  Be the guy who knows that new tool better than anyone else. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the process, youâ€™ll also be the guy who uses the tool the way the people who developed that tool intended it to be used. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hereâ€™s a truth Iâ€™ve observed.Â  Everyone wants to use whatever tool theyâ€™ve just started using like the last tool they used.Â  And then, when it doesnâ€™t, the new tool â€œdoesnâ€™t work.â€Â  This one truth has done more to hold our industry back than any other one thing I can point to.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Design-Patterns&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Design-Patterns&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Design Patterns&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Design Patterns&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Learn the basic design patterns for your environment.Â  But go beyond learning the pattern.Â  Learn why the pattern exist.Â  What problem does it solve?Â  Be able to recognize counterfeits.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Architecture&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Architecture&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Architecture&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Architecture&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Along with Design Patterns, learn the basics of Architecture.Â  Hereâ€™s a hint.Â  All good architecture answers the question, â€œHow can I write code that is not dependent on any other code?â€Â  This is one of the reasons I love Functional Programming.Â  By design, Functional code is not dependent on other code.Â  Dependencies are passed into the function.Â  But you can achieve similar objectives using Object Oriented programming languages or even Procedural languages.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Single-Responsibility&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Single-Responsibility&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Single Responsibility&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Single Responsibility&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Granular is better than Monolithic!Â  Donâ€™t be afraid to split things up.Â  Use components.Â  Compose classes of other classes.Â  Components of other components.Â  And most important of all, donâ€™t create a Utils class of any kind.Â  In some languages this is easier than others.Â  But if you can, any method you have in a Utils class should be a function in its own file.Â  If you canâ€™t do that, maybe each function belongs in its own class unless there is a strong argument for putting them together in a class that can be reasonably named in a way that obviously groups those methods. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Another pet peeve of mine is putting multiple classes or interfaces in one file. Split them up!Â  Donâ€™t make me go hunting for the source of a class. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The ONLY time you might be excused from splitting things up is if the only place the code is being used is in the fileâ€™s main class.Â  But once you make that class available to the outside world, out it comes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Alternate-Languages&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Alternate-Languages&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Alternate Languages&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Alternate Languages&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;This should go without saying.Â  But the more languages you learn, the better programmer you will become.Â  I remember when I started learning C++, I had a hard time understanding references.Â  And then I started learning Clipper (a dBase III compiler) and something they said made references make sense suddenly. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And this has been my experience all along.Â  Every new thing I learn helps me see problems in a slightly different perspective.Â  Making my code in every language I know that much better.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Code-Reviews&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Code-Reviews&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Code Reviews&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Code Reviews&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;So far, everything Iâ€™ve mentioned is something you can do on your own.Â  This last one will require at least one other person.Â  Maybe you can buddy up with someone at work for this. &lt;/p&gt;
