&lt;p&gt;Notice that we have a &lt;code&gt;default&lt;/code&gt; in our switch statement.Â  Donâ€™t forget to add this.Â  It isnâ€™t an accident.Â  You see, when we register our Reducers and Effects with the store and then subsequently dispatch actions to them, all the reducers and effects get called.Â  In the case of reducers, if you donâ€™t return something for each one of them, youâ€™ll end up with a store that doesnâ€™t know what kind of state it is in.Â  So, always return the current state as your default. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The one thing that may not be obvious here is that the Reducer is a function.Â  Not a class.Â  This means you canâ€™t inject other classes into it.Â  This is one of the reasons that the file is named &lt;code&gt;wait.reducer.ts&lt;/code&gt; and not &lt;code&gt;wait.reducer**s**.ts&lt;/code&gt;. But, Effects are different.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;Effects&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Effects&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Effects&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Effects&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Effects are classes.Â  Each Effect within the Effects class is a member variable.Â  This means, we name our Effects file for Wait, &lt;code&gt;wait.effects.ts&lt;/code&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, remember I said that Effects were for things that caused side effects?Â  You may wonder, why kind of side effect does our Wait stuff need? &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Under normal circumstances, not any.Â  However, you can get into a situation in development mode where one of the safe guards Angular provides for you detects that youâ€™ve changed the state of wait multiple times in a change detection loop.Â  Angular expects changes to be static. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One way we can deal with this is to delay incrementing and decrementing to another change detection loop using setTimeout() indirectly. &lt;/p&gt;
