&lt;h2 id=&#34;Returning-No-Actions&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Returning-No-Actions&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Returning No Actions&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Returning No Actions&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;There have been times in the past where I didnâ€™t want to return an Action from my Effect.Â  Not knowing any better, I just returned the Object Literal, &lt;code&gt;&amp;#123;type: &amp;#39;noop&amp;#39;&amp;#125;&lt;/code&gt;.Â  But there is a much better way. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;BTW, did you know that unless you tell NgRX otherwise, all @Effects must return an Action? &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, what is the better way?Â  It turns out that the guys who wrote NgRX already thought of the possibility that you wouldnâ€™t want to return an action from an @Effect.Â  All you need to do is to pass the object literal &lt;code&gt;&amp;#123;dispatch: false&amp;#125;&lt;/code&gt; to the @Effect() decoractor. &lt;/p&gt;
