&lt;p&gt;But, do you know why it works? &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That &lt;code&gt;switchMap()&lt;/code&gt; bit expects that youâ€™ll return an observable.Â  It subscribes to it and passes the data inside the observable to the &lt;code&gt;map()&lt;/code&gt; that follows.Â  Kind of like how the &lt;code&gt;async&lt;/code&gt; pipe works in our templates. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cool thing about this is that you can chain subscriptions together using this.Â  It isnâ€™t just some cleaver way of getting the results of a service into your final action that you will return.Â  Iâ€™ve used &lt;code&gt;switchMap()&lt;/code&gt; to get data from the store and pass that on to a &lt;code&gt;switchMap()&lt;/code&gt; that call my service with that data. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The only thing you need to watch out for is that your observable is either a cold observable or that you call &lt;code&gt;.first()&lt;/code&gt; so you it becomes a cold observable.Â  Otherwise, youâ€™ll end up in an infinite loop.Â  Ask me how I know :).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Grouping-Observables&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Grouping-Observables&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Grouping Observables&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Grouping Observables&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Chaining observables together using &lt;code&gt;switchMap()&lt;/code&gt; works well when the output only needs to be used by the next function in the chain.Â  But what about when you need to use the results from two different observables at once.Â  There are a couple of different ways you might do this. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One function you might consider using is &lt;code&gt;withLatestFrom()&lt;/code&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;figure class=&#34;highlight typescript&#34;&gt;&lt;table&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;gutter&#34;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;code&#34;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;firstObservable&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;  .&lt;span class=&#34;title function_&#34;&gt;withLatestFrom&lt;/span&gt;(secondObservable, &lt;span class=&#34;function&#34;&gt;(&lt;span class=&#34;params&#34;&gt;[firstResult, secondResult]&lt;/span&gt;) =&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;  &lt;span class=&#34;comment&#34;&gt;// your code here)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;or if you have more than two you need to combine, you can use &lt;code&gt;combineLatest()&lt;/code&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Another way you might consider combining them is with &lt;code&gt;forkJoin()&lt;/code&gt; although that might be the last tool you reach for.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Single-Responsibility&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Single-Responsibility&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Single Responsibility&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Single Responsibility&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Another mistake Iâ€™ve been making is trying to make my Effect do too much.Â  If I restrict my effect to only doing one thing at a time and always returning one or more actions, they become much easier to manage.Â  Maybe this has only be my problem.Â  But once I saw what switchMap() could do for me, the light bulb went on in my brain.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Returning-Multiple-Actions&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Returning-Multiple-Actions&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Returning Multiple Actions&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Returning Multiple Actions&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;And speaking of returning one or more actions, it is possible to return multiple actions from an Effect using.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;figure class=&#34;highlight typescript&#34;&gt;&lt;table&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;gutter&#34;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;4&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;5&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;6&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;7&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;8&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;code&#34;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;.&lt;span class=&#34;title function_&#34;&gt;mergeMap&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;  &lt;span class=&#34;function&#34;&gt;(&lt;span class=&#34;params&#34;&gt; result: &lt;span class=&#34;built_in&#34;&gt;string&lt;/span&gt;[] &lt;/span&gt;) =&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;#123;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;    &lt;span class=&#34;keyword&#34;&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;title class_&#34;&gt;Observable&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;span class=&#34;title function_&#34;&gt;from&lt;/span&gt;([ &lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;      &lt;span class=&#34;keyword&#34;&gt;new&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;title class_&#34;&gt;ActionOne&lt;/span&gt;( result ), &lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;      &lt;span class=&#34;keyword&#34;&gt;new&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;title class_&#34;&gt;ActionTwo&lt;/span&gt;() &lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;    ]);&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;  &amp;#125;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;

 &lt;p&gt;For the last 18 months, Iâ€™ve been working for an organization that has what some might consider a unique requirement.Â  Because of where our applicationâ€™s data is sourced, we need to aggregate data on the client side rather than on the server.Â  What this means is that for any one screen, we may make multiple calls to the server to grab all the data we need.Â  Fortunately, because we adopted NgRX early in our adoption of Angular, we could avoid a lot of the headaches associated with client-side aggregation. &lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;/uploads/2017/09/2017-10-03.png&#34; title=&#34;Using NgRX to Cleanly Aggregate Data&#34;&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;Photo credit: &lt;a href=&#34;//www.flickr.com/photos/gsfc/14486243743/&#34;&gt;NASA Goddard Photo and Video&lt;/a&gt; via &lt;a href=&#34;//visualhunt.com/re/296da9&#34;&gt;Visualhunt&lt;/a&gt; &amp;#x2F; &lt;a href=&#34;//creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/&#34;&gt; CC BY&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span id=&#34;more&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt; 

&lt;h2 id=&#34;The-Problem&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#The-Problem&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;The Problem&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;The Problem&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are multiple ways this problem might manifest itself in an application.Â  But one of the most common is a basic search screen that displays a list of results.Â  Everything is simple when your data comes back with all the data you need.Â  But in our case, the data that is returned might contain all but one or two fields that we need.Â  Those fields exist in other end points.Â  To keep the basic problem small, letâ€™s just assume that you search for a list of records.Â  That search returns 10 items.Â  For each of those records, you now need to make two more calls to retrieve the content of the two missing fields.Â  This means that to get a complete result set back, you need to make a total of 21 calls.Â  The problem becomes even worse if you have a total of 100 records, or you now have 3 fields that you need to retrieve for each row.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;The-Old-Way&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#The-Old-Way&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;The Old Way&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;The Old Way&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Prior to using NgRX, the main way we might solve this problem would be to introduce callback hell, or promise hell if you are that lucky.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Make a call for the original list&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When the list gets returned&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Iterate through the records and&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Make a call for Child Record One&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When callback returns, add the new value to the parent record&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Make a call for Child Record Two&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When the callback returns, add the new value to the parent record&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Once all the calls have returned, return the list so it can be displayed.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As you can see, this not only becomes difficult to manage, but it also introduces a system that is going to be perceived as slow. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But, now, we can do better.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Using-NgRX&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Using-NgRX&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Using NgRX&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Using NgRX&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;By using NgRX, we use a series of Effects to retrieve our data, typically via a Service.Â  When the effect is done, it returns the results to a reducer which puts them in our store entity for us. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The basic work flow looks like something like this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Dispatch an action to get the main results&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Effect hears the action and makes a call for the top-level list&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When the list returns,&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Iterate through the records and&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;we dispatch an action to get Child Record One&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;we dispatch an action to get Child Record Two&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Return an Action that will use a reducer to fill our list&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Child Record One Effect hears the actions for each of the rows&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When each of the values are retrieved the Effect returns an Action that uses a Reducer to put the value in the store&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Child Record Two Effect hears the actions for each of the rows&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When each of the values are retrieved, the Effect returns an Action that uses a Reducer to put the value in the store&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Youâ€™ll notice, we no longer have the nesting mess that we had using the old way and we can list our results as soon as the first set of data is returned.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Meanwhile-back-on-our-View&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Meanwhile-back-on-our-View&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Meanwhile, back on our View&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Meanwhile, back on our View&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now, there are two ways you can deal with displaying this information in your view and it all depends on what you are doing. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The easy way is to just let the View display the information as it comes back.Â  Most of the time this will work.Â  If you need to filter your data in the display once it comes back, you will need to decide if data that doesnâ€™t have the child fields yet should, or should not be displayed. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Another quirk I had to deal with was that we were displaying child rows with child rows.Â  Letting the data display as we got it back gave the screen a kind of exploding effect.Â  For this, I added a debounceTime(500) to the store observer so that the screen only updated once all the data had been retrieved.Â  Using the pattern above was still easier to reason about than the old way, we just didnâ€™t get the added benefit of being able to see the data as it was being retrieved.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Watch-Out&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Watch-Out&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Watch Out!&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Watch Out!&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;One of the wrong ways you might be tempted to use this pattern would be to chain all the child stuff in one effect and dispatch actions to your reducers from within the one Effect.Â  This would be a mistake.Â  Sure, it would work.Â  But now because your effect is doing more than one thing, your code becomes MUCH harder to reason about.Â  While each of your Effects may ultimately call the same reducer function, or not, you definitely want to have a separate set of Actions and Effects that retrieve the data from the server.&lt;/p&gt;

 &lt;p&gt;As Iâ€™ve been interviewing for a new contract, the question, â€œHow do we Upgrade to Angular from â€¦?â€ has come up several times. Â And as Iâ€™ve thought about the question, several patterns have emerged. &lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;/uploads/2017/09/2017-09-26.jpg&#34; title=&#34;Upgrade Angular from ...&#34;&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;Photo credit: &lt;a href=&#34;//www.flickr.com/photos/archer10/12414442945/&#34;&gt;archer10 (Dennis) 102M Views&lt;/a&gt; via &lt;a href=&#34;//visualhunt.com/re/426124&#34;&gt;Visualhunt&lt;/a&gt; &amp;#x2F; &lt;a href=&#34;//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/&#34;&gt; CC BY-SA&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span id=&#34;more&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt; 

&lt;h2 id=&#34;From-a-Portal&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#From-a-Portal&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;From a Portal&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;From a Portal&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;The first time I was asked this question, the team I was talking with had an existing Web 1.0 site setup using WebSphere Portal. Â Not something that you can easily plug any Single Page Application (SPA) into. But all is not lost. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One of the easiest ways to solve the problem is to create a reverse proxy. Â One popular tool for this is mod_proxy for the Apache server. Â If you are using IIS, you could use URL Rewrite rules to setup a reverse proxy. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In either case, you will need to setup rules that ensure that anyone trying to access a URL that is still on the old portal site would still be able to access that directly. Â Once that is in place, you would create one page, or maybe a set of related pages, at a time and stand them up on another server. Â Then you would change your rules so that anyone trying to access the old URLs that are no longer being served by the old site get redirected to the new SPA application. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, this sounds pretty simple. Â But, I imagine keeping everything in sync as you go might be more of a pain that you might imagine. Â If you have pages that link to each other, youâ€™ll need to convert links to routes as you go. Â Say you convert page one. Â It still has links to the old site. Â Not a big problem. Â But as the pages it is linking to now become part of the SPA, youâ€™ll want to convert those links to route directives. Â One way you might mitigate this issue is to convert pages with the fewest links out first. Â It might help to create a graph, or at least a spreadsheet, to help you manage the interdependent relationships. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;An added advantage of this setup is that any pages in the portal that have relatively static content, and any resources, can be cached, or even moved, to the proxy server where they will probably be served up faster than the original portal.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;From-a-Web-1-0-Site&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#From-a-Web-1-0-Site&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;From a Web 1.0 Site&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;From a Web 1.0 Site&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Switching from an existing Web 1.0 site might be a bit easier. Â Although, using the proxy method there still might be the best choice. Â Many of the same issues exist. Â But in the case of an existing Web 1.0 site that doesnâ€™t depend on a portal, youâ€™ll probably have greater control over the server. Â Again, you are probably running the site on Apache, nginx, or IIS. Â In all of those cases, you can setup a rule that says, â€œif you canâ€™t find the URL, load up this page over here instead.â€ Â Where â€œthis page over hereâ€ is your Angular site you are converting to. Â Youâ€™ll need to implement something like this anyhow for your Angular SPA to work correctly, so this is probably the least amount of extra work to get you where you need to be. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Then, you convert a page or a set of related pages at a time like I described in the Portal implementation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;From-Another-Framework&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#From-Another-Framework&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;From Another Framework&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;From Another Framework&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Letâ€™s say that you are moving from React, or some other framework to Angular. Â I know of a company that is doing just this. Â The wrinkle is, they have no plans on converting their existing pages to Angular. Â This makes the transition relatively simple. Â You setup rules on your server, similar to how you would setup a conversion from a Web 1.0 site. Â â€œURLs that look like this, go to the old index.html page and URLs that look like that go to the new index.html page.â€ &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once again, youâ€™ll need to keep track of routes as you change from one to the other. Â But it is manageable.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Converting-AngularJS-to-Angular&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Converting-AngularJS-to-Angular&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Converting AngularJS to Angular&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Converting AngularJS to Angular&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Yes, I know ngUpgrade exist. Â But, if you donâ€™t need to use it, why would you. Â ngUpgrade exist so you can embed Angular in AngularJS or AngularJS in Angular. Â But, it might make more sense to create a new SPA for Angular and have the two sites reference each other similar to how you would do this for a Web 1.0 site or if you were converting from an entirely different framework. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The reason I recommend using the two-site method first is because Angular really is a different framework. Â There are similarities between AngularJS and Angular. Â But that is all they are. Â What if you just pretended they werenâ€™t at all related. Â That the ngUpdate bridge didnâ€™t exist. Â Wouldnâ€™t that make life just a bit easier in the long run? Â I think it would.&lt;/p&gt;

 &lt;p&gt;I made a tweak to my Angular code process over the last month or so that has resulted in greater productivity in my development environment and fewer bugs. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, I didnâ€™t make this change because I thought it would improve my productivity.Â  At least that wasnâ€™t the primary reason.Â  I made the change because I thought it would reduce the chance of introducing bugs into my code.Â  And while it does reduce the number of bugs in my code, the result has been generally improved productivity. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What is this great secret? &lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;/uploads/2017/09/2017-09-12.jpg&#34; title=&#34;This One Tweak Improved my Angular Code&#34;&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;Photo credit: &lt;a href=&#34;//www.flickr.com/photos/sheila_sund/36859429262/&#34;&gt;docoverachiever&lt;/a&gt; via &lt;a href=&#34;//visualhunt.com/re/d75fb5&#34;&gt;Visual Hunt&lt;/a&gt; &amp;#x2F; &lt;a href=&#34;//creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/&#34;&gt; CC BY&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
