 &lt;p&gt;Over the last week Iâ€™ve gradually come to the realization that the fundamental reason why most people have trouble with JavaScript is because it doesnâ€™t fit their mental model of how programming should be done. Â This isnâ€™t to say that most programmers donâ€™t manage to achieve their end goal. Â But if you sit back and take an objective look at the code we end up writing, you have to admit, the code ends up being quite ugly. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, this isnâ€™t a dig at the way weâ€™ve been doing things. Â Weâ€™ve all been doing the best we can with what we have. Â But, the JavaScript world has progressed and there is a better mental model that has developed and should even be expanded which will allow us to develop more complex and feature rich applications now and well into the future. &lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;/uploads/2017/09/2017-09-05.jpg&#34; title=&#34;Thinking in JavaScript&#34;&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;Photo credit: &lt;a href=&#34;//www.flickr.com/photos/froderik/8283727226/&#34;&gt;freddie boy&lt;/a&gt; via &lt;a href=&#34;//visualhunt.com/re/fb4c57&#34;&gt;Visual Hunt&lt;/a&gt; &amp;#x2F; &lt;a href=&#34;//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/&#34;&gt; CC BY-SA&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span id=&#34;more&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt; 

&lt;h2 id=&#34;Where-Weâ€™ve-Been&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Where-Weâ€™ve-Been&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Where Weâ€™ve Been&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Where Weâ€™ve Been&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Iâ€™ve been saying for years that the thing that holds most programmers back is that they always want to treat whatever new thing they are using like the last thing they were using. Â And nowhere has this displayed itself more apparently than with JavaScript. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Take the most obvious of examples. Â Everyone knows, or should know by now, that JavaScript is not really object-oriented. Â And yet, weâ€™ve been trying to force JavaScript to BE object-oriented pretty much from the beginning. Â This hasnâ€™t been such a big problem, although one could argue that by trying to make JavaScript object-oriented, weâ€™ve prevented it from being able to do some of the things it does best. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Where we really run into trouble is with the event based, and often asynchronous nature of JavaScript. Think about this. Â For years, weâ€™ve been trying to synchronize something that is inherently asynchronous. Â And this is where the real trouble begins. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First, we had call back. Then promises. Now Observables. Soon async and await. And while callbacks are how the asynchronous nature of JavaScript is handle under the hood, the others are attempts to tame the asynchronous beast. Â Especially async and await.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Why&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Why&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Why?&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Why?&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now, this is where we are. Constantly trying to make JavaScript be something it isnâ€™t.Â But, why is this? &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I believe it is because we are trying to impose models onto JavaScript that were useful in our desktop and server-side applications. Â MVC, MVVM, Object-Oriented, and others all grew up in a world that was both synchronous, multi-threaded, and lent themselves well to an object-oriented model. Â As various frameworks have evolved, the attempt has been to take these familiar models and apply them to an asynchronous, single threaded and not really object-oriented. Â From where I sit, I am amazed any of this worked at all. Â It seems to me it should have failed long ago.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;A-Light-in-The-Darkness&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#A-Light-in-The-Darkness&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;A Light in The Darkness&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;A Light in The Darkness&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Hey, Iâ€™ve been stuck in the old school model too. Â But, Iâ€™m starting to think there may be a better way. Â Iâ€™ve written about Redux and NgRX a lot on this blog. Â Iâ€™ve fielded a lot of questions on the Angular slack channel. Â Most of the questions revolve around the basic question of handling multiple asynchronous calls for data as part of one action. Â All of the questions presuppose you would need to make each of the calls for data and then use some method of waiting for everything to return and assemble the data before moving on. Â In each case, I recommend an alternative. Â What if, each call was a unique action. Â When each returns, another action is fired that places the return data in the appropriate store, or sub store. Â In this model, we donâ€™t care when the data comes back. Â When it comes back, we deal with it appropriately.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;An-Example&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#An-Example&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;An Example&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;An Example&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Letâ€™s go with one of the more common examples I see. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I need to make a request for a set of records. Â Once I have the results, for each record in the result, I need to go get a set of child records. Â Here is how I would deal with this at a very high level using NgRX. Â Iâ€™m sure this would work for multiple Redux patterns but they may call things by different names.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Fire an Action that request the main set of records.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The appropriate Effect responds to the action by making an AJAX call for the data.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When the AJAX call returns,&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;fire an Action that puts the main records in the store.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;for each record in the result fire an Action asking for the child record(s).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The appropriate Effect(s) responds to the request for child records by making AJAX calls.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When the data returns fire an Action that places the data in the store.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Since your view is listening for changes on the entities in your store, it will update as the data comes in. Even better if you setup a debounce on your listener, the screen will update only when all of the data has been retrieved.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;The-Key-Concept&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#The-Key-Concept&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;The Key Concept&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;The Key Concept&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;The key concept here is that we no longer care WHEN something happens. Â We only care THAT it happens. Â And rather than trying to setup forkJoins() or some other mechanism to flatten this all out, our code ends up being quite simple. Â Discrete bits of functionality. Â And now, all our asynchronous code becomes Reactive code. Â We no longer need to flatten anything out.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Server-Side&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Server-Side&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Server Side&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Server Side&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Sadly, on the server side, things arenâ€™t quite so easy. Â At best we are tied to an implementation Observables and the various methods of combining Observables. Â But I could also see some kind of client&amp;#x2F;server implementation that used a framework like SignalR or Socket.io so that as the various Observables complete, the data on the client would get updated. Â An interesting way to make all of the AJAXy calls rather transparent to the user.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Taking-it-To-the-Next-Level&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Taking-it-To-the-Next-Level&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Taking it To the Next Level&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Taking it To the Next Level&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;You may call me a dreamer, but what if we made a JavaScript framework that was all message driven and reactive like Iâ€™ve described above? Â Weâ€™ve done it before. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When Windows was first created in ran on single core CPUs. Â It was essentially single threaded. Â The way it worked was primarily by putting â€œeventsâ€ on a que and then sending the events to the appropriate application that needed to know about them. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you applied this model to JavaScript and folded in what Iâ€™ve described above, you could easily have a system that appeared to be multi-threaded even though it was single threaded at its core.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Donâ€™t-Throw-the-Baby-Out-â€¦&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Donâ€™t-Throw-the-Baby-Out-â€¦&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Donâ€™t Throw the Baby Out â€¦&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Donâ€™t Throw the Baby Out â€¦&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now, you may think Iâ€™m endorsing throwing out object-oriented JavaScript. Â Actually, I think most of the View stuff we do lends itself well to object-oriented programming. Â But, most of our business rules lend themselves better to the model Iâ€™ve described above. Â Functional and Reactive.&lt;/p&gt;

 &lt;p&gt;While testing Components is possible, it is not easy and is often pointless. Â Using the Model View Presenter pattern, or a variation of it, solves the problem. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hereâ€™s the deal. Long time readers of my blog know Iâ€™ve been a proponent of Unit Testing for a very long time. While I was learning React, I went through the exercise of trying to write test as I was learning. Â Now, the great thing about Angular and React is that it is possible to test your components. Â The problem with testing components is that you are either testing that your HTML ended up in the right spot, that Angular directives did what they should, or you are evaluating the DOM to verify that component logic worked. Â In most cases, putting tests that do any of these at the component level is the wrong way to test. &lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;/uploads/2017/08/2017-08-27.jpg&#34; title=&#34;Model View Presenter, Angular, and Testing&#34;&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;Photo credit: &lt;a href=&#34;//www.flickr.com/photos/tamworthboroughcouncil/15657023428/&#34;&gt;Tamworth Borough Council&lt;/a&gt; via &lt;a href=&#34;//visualhunt.com/re/e21893&#34;&gt;Visualhunt.com&lt;/a&gt; &amp;#x2F; &lt;a href=&#34;//creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/&#34;&gt; CC BY&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span id=&#34;more&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt; 

&lt;h2 id=&#34;Evaluating-HTML&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Evaluating-HTML&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Evaluating HTML&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Evaluating HTML&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Ignoring for a second that setting up a component test is awkward, the question I want to address here is, â€œis that really an appropriate test?â€ &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If all your smart component does is pass data down to dumb component, all you really need to verify is that given a dumb component with an html fragment, and another one with another fragment, they will all end up sequentially after each other. Â It is a pretty easy test to setup. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But all youâ€™ve ended up testing is that Angular does what it says it will. It wonâ€™t tell you what you canâ€™t already see by running the code. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dumb components are even more obvious. Â Letâ€™s go for something obvious. Â You have a ngFor that allows you to display a list of HTML. Â You setup your component so that it has an array of three known items, you pass that into the component, do a change detection cycle, and verify that your HTML displays as expected. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Great, youâ€™ve verified that Angular works again. Â You will have a hard time convincing me that youâ€™ve really tested anything.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Angular-Directives&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Angular-Directives&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Angular Directives&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Angular Directives&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;In this case, you are going to try to verify that when you click on a component, or pass it some data, orâ€¦ whatever, that Angular does what it should. Â Maybe you do need to verify that when you click an element, something else happens. Â But this is not the place. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You might create an integration test, which would, by definition, take longer to run. Â It would be better if you tested this using an end to end test. Â But testing this as a unit test, doesnâ€™t tell you much more than that Angular has said that it would. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;â€œBut, I need to verify that the code in my event handler does what it should!â€ Â You might complain. Â Yes, you do, but you donâ€™t need to fire a click event to do that, just call the event handler.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Big-Fat-Hairy-Logic&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Big-Fat-Hairy-Logic&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Big Fat Hairy Logic&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Big Fat Hairy Logic&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;And then there is that â€œbig fat hairy logicâ€ issue. Â Youâ€™ve created some sort of component that has some rather complex logic. Â OK, that happens. Â A grid control is a perfect example. Â But, maybe your logic is in the wrong place?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;A-Better-Solution&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#A-Better-Solution&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;A Better Solution&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;A Better Solution&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;There is a design pattern called â€œModel View Presenterâ€ Like all of the MV* patterns it aims to separate out logic from the view so that we can test things easier. Â It was popular with WebForms in ASP.NET when that was how you wrote ASP.NET web sites. Â The way this worked was that you would create an Interface for your WebForm that represented all of the things you wanted to have access to from your logic code. Â Your presenter. Â All your component or page code did was respond to events on the page and expose data to the data driven forms. Â In a lot of ways, Angular isnâ€™t much different from WebForms. Â Your TypeScript file is essentially a â€œcode-behindâ€ file and your template is similar to an ASPX page. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The beauty of the MVP pattern is that when you do it right, your component has no logic at all. Â It renders data and responds to events by calling down to the presenter. Â In an Angular world, I doubt the Presenter would ever need to call up to the view. Â This is prefect. Â Now I can create a test for my component logic in a way very similar to how I would test any other Injectable. Â Because Injectables are what we are going to use here.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;Injectable-Presenters&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Injectable-Presenters&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Injectable Presenters&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Injectable Presenters&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;For the point of illustration, letâ€™s assume that all components would follow this pattern. Â Now a simple component would have four files instead of the normal three.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;*.component.ts&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;*.component.html&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;*.component.css&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;*.component.presenter.ts&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;*.component.presenter.ts&lt;/code&gt; file is our new Injectable. Â Any properties in our component would pass on down to the presenter. Â Any methods, which should be few to none, would pass on down to the presenter. Â The presenter is where we do all the work.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;Make-the-Presenter-Available-to-the-Component&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Make-the-Presenter-Available-to-the-Component&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Make the Presenter Available to the Component&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Make the Presenter Available to the Component&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now, if youâ€™ve studied the Angular tutorials, you probably already know this, but my bet is most people programming the new Angular donâ€™t. Â You can make an Injectable available by providing it in a module, or by providing it in a component. Â If you provide it in the module, it is globally available. Â If you provide it in the component, it is only available to that component or its child components. Â This is perfect for our use case here. Â So, we provide it in our component and then inject it into our componentâ€™s constructor. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Everything else we might have injected into our component can now be injected into our presenter.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Look-Ma-No-DOM&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Look-Ma-No-DOM&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Look Ma, No DOM&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Look Ma, No DOM&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;The side effect of this pattern is now, the complexity of the methods in our component should be 1. Â This means they donâ€™t really need to be tested. Â And because they donâ€™t need to be tested, we donâ€™t really need a DOM available to run our tests. Â This makes it MUCH easier to use jsDOM to run our unit test without having to wire in a bunch of polyfills just to make it all â€œwork.â€&lt;/p&gt;

 &lt;p&gt;If youâ€™ve been programming JavaScript based applications for any length of time, youâ€™ve probably already made the progression from callback hell to promises, but just to recap. Â Whenever we make any kind of asynchronous call in JavaScript, we need to provide a callback function to the call so that, when the call completes, the function can be called with any resulting data. Â Function calls you may typically make that need this kind of feature are &lt;code&gt;setTimeout()&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;setInterval(),&lt;/code&gt; and AJAX calls using the various libraries that support this. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The problem with using callbacks is that you can end up with â€œCallback Hellâ€ where you have callbacks inside of other callbacks. Â Our code becomes messy and difficult to reason about. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To try to flatten this situation out, promises were created. Â Instead of creating a callback function and passing it into the asynchronous function, the asynchronous function returns a promise that has a function we can pass our function into. Â This function can return yet another promise. Â The result is that instead of having nested callbacks, all of our callbacks live at the same level. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, in the process, we lost the ability to cancel an asynchronous function using callbacks. Â Most of the time, this was not a huge concern, but in the case of AJAX calls, we did end up making more request than we really needed to. Â Most people never even recognized this as an issue. Â But if you go and take a look at some of your older code, you will see that you have several places where the code would work more efficiently if you were able to cancel a call that was being superseded by a new call. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Meanwhile, some additional functions were added to JavaScript Arrays. Â Maybe youâ€™ve seen some of them? Â map(), reduce(), and filter() are three of the more common functions. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What? Â You havenâ€™t seen these? Â If you have and you know how they work, you can skip this next section. Â But, if you havenâ€™t, pay careful attention because this next section is critical to understanding how Observables work. &lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;/uploads/2017/08/2017-08-08.jpg&#34; title=&#34;Angular Observable Secrets Revealed&#34;&gt; Photo via &lt;a href=&#34;//visualhunt.com/re/4ba464&#34;&gt;VisualHunt.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
