 &lt;p&gt;In the old world where all of our pages were on the server and every change on the client side required a full round trip to the server, each page was a unique URL on the server. Â In the SPA world, we only load one â€œPageâ€ from the server and the client takes care of making it look like we have moved from one page to another. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When done well, we can create pages that reuse existing content on the screen causing a minimal screen refresh while still allowing the user to link to a specific â€œPageâ€ in our application. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These â€œPagesâ€ are called â€œRoutesâ€ Â As in, here is the route to some code I want to execute. &lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;/uploads/2017/07/2017-07-18.png&#34; title=&#34;How to Implement Angular 2+ Routing&#34;&gt; Photo via &lt;a href=&#34;//visualhunt.com/re/9589c4&#34;&gt;Visual Hunt&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span id=&#34;more&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;  Sounds pretty cool. Â But there is a down side that shows up every time someone tries to do this for the first time. Â You wonâ€™t see this problem until the first time you try to deploy your code because the development server handles this issue for you. 

&lt;p&gt;The problem is this. Â When a server receives a request from the browser, it tries to find that file on the server. Â If it doesnâ€™t exist, the server returns a 404 error. Â File not found. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Most servers provide ways of circumventing this issue by providing rules. Â Essentially, you write a server rule that says, â€œIf the browser ask for a file that doesnâ€™t exist, send them back index.html instead.â€ Â You may need to provide exceptions or otherwise refine the rule if your server is also rerouting other traffic. If you are running on an IIS server, &lt;a href=&#34;/asp-net-angular-js-html5mode/&#34;&gt;I wrote instructions for how to take care of this issue&lt;/a&gt; for AngularJS (1.x). Â The instructions work for any client side framework that implements routing. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Assuming you have that end of things working correctly, here are the steps to get basic routing working in your Angular application.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Define-Your-Routes&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Define-Your-Routes&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Define Your Routes&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Define Your Routes&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;While we could easily define our routes in app.module.ts, the code we write will be much easier to maintain if we create a separate module file named app-routes.module.ts. Â So to start, create an app-routes.module.ts file right next to your app.module.ts file. Â You can do this with the Angular CLI by typing the following in the command line from within the src&amp;#x2F;app directory: &lt;/p&gt;
