&lt;h2 id=&#34;Guards&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Guards&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Guards&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Guards&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Guards control access to our routes. Â What happens if you have a route that only certain people should have access to. Â Like an admin page. Â Sure, you could leave the link off so no one can click the link to get to the page, but that doesnâ€™t prevent someone from pasting the link to the forbidden page into the address bar of the browser and getting there anyhow. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In Angular, we have four kinds of guards and two ways of creating them. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The four types of guards are:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;CanActivate&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;CanActivateChild&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;CanDeactivate&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;CanLoad&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you follow my advice and always lazy load your routes, than the two you will most often use are CanLoad and CanDeactivate. Â CanLoad provides rules for lazy loading a module. Â CanDeactive provides rules for leaving a route. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you decide to bundle routes together, then you may also need CanActivate and CanActivateChild. Â CanActivate is exactly what it sounds like. Â Can I activate this route? Â CanActivateChild would go on a route definition that has a childrenâ€™s collection. Â This rule determines if I can activate the children. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To use Guards in our application, the first thing we need to do is to define them. Â The easiest way to define them is as a function that returns a boolean value, a boolean Observable, or a boolean Promise. Â For our purposes here, we will just return a boolean value. Â But when you have some asynchronous call you need to make to determine if we should return true or false, youâ€™ll want to return an Observable or a Promise. Â I favor Observables. &lt;/p&gt;
