&lt;h2 id=&#34;Defending-against-confidence&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Defending-against-confidence&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Defending against confidence&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Defending against confidence&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;And this leads nicely into my next point.Â Just because someone is confident, doesnâ€™t mean they are right.Â And some people will, knowingly or not, project confidence to bullshit their way to where they want to go.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;When-Two-People-Meet&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#When-Two-People-Meet&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;When Two People Meet&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;When Two People Meet&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Basic social interaction theory says that when two people meet, a pecking order will be established such that one will be the leader and the other the follower. In a group, a leader will emerge. If you are a speaker, you can leverage this by identifying the perceived leader and speaking to them.Â Everyone else will follow.&lt;/p&gt;
