&lt;p&gt;And yet, the way many people act, they would like things to stay the same.Â  And I ask, â€œWhy?â€Â  So that 30 years from today we are still struggling with the same issues we are today?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Maturity&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Maturity&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Maturity&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Maturity&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Every new technology goes through essentially the same process.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At first, it is brand new.Â  No one really knows the best way to use it.Â  Some are better planned than others, others were accidents and were subject to more discovery than others.Â  JavaScript was one of those that was more of an accident.Â  So, weâ€™ve spent a lot of time trying to figure out the best way to use it.Â  Think about this, if we had known then what we know now, donâ€™t you think JavaScript would have been designed differently from the beginning? At some point the new technology either dies, or matures enough that people start experimenting with how to use it best.Â  This is the place where design patterns are developed and features are added to the language.Â  This is the part of the cycle I love and is generally where I tend to jump into the technology.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Eventually the technology matures and gets boring.Â  This is where I tend to jump off.Â  Java and .NET are in this phase.Â  The patterns for both are well established.Â  What features are being added are at the â€œnice to haveâ€ level.Â  But generally everything most people need to be able to do can already be done with what is available.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We are currently at the beginning of the experimental phase.Â  Expect to see A LOT of change in the next several years.Â  If you donâ€™t like it, move to a more mature technology that wonâ€™t change so much on you.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Conclusion&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Conclusion&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Conclusion&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Conclusion&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;The final factor that magnifies all of the problems with JavaScript Iâ€™ve mentioned is that for way too long, JavaScript has been the language of Script Kiddies.Â  These are â€œprogrammersâ€ who think that because they can achieve some sort of animation or validation on an HTML page by copy and pasting JavaScript they are real programmers.Â  So when someone with much more experience comes along and shows them a better way to program, instead of trying to learn they assert that this new way is wrong, or ridiculous, or declare they are going to take their toys and go to some other castle.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The problem is, all the castles are now occupied by Kings and Queens instead of children who donâ€™t know any better.&lt;/p&gt;

 &lt;p&gt;On the subject of Angular2 Architecture, the perception is that Angular 2 is a highly-opinionated architecture. But even though there is a &lt;a href=&#34;/angular.io/styleguide&#34;&gt;style guide for Angular 2&lt;/a&gt;, there are a lot of decisions that still need to be made when working on any but the most trivial of applications. And even then, since most applications take on a life of their own, one could make the case that you need to make these decisions for any application you are building regardless of the initial size. Applications grow up. But, thatâ€™s another blog post&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Iâ€™ve identified, and have formed opinions about 5 areas that Angular 2 leaves open for decisions. Areas that if you donâ€™t spend time considering the choices and making decisions could cost you in the future&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The five areas Iâ€™ve identified are:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Handling Forms&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Page State Management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Component State Management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Data Flow&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Client Side Data&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
