&lt;p&gt;If you are using IIS and ASP.NET, you might find this article I wrote about using &lt;a href=&#34;/asp-net-angular-js-html5mode/&#34;&gt;Angular, Routing, and ASP.NET&lt;/a&gt; useful.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Enabling-Routing&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Enabling-Routing&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Enabling Routing&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Enabling Routing&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Since the Angular CLI has included the packages youâ€™ll need to enable routing, there is nothing to install. We just need to write some code.&lt;/p&gt;
