&lt;p&gt;If you are using software that requires you to assign bugs to an individual, make that individual the Scrum Master, Product Owner, or Project Manager (if you arenâ€™t doing Scrum).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Organizational-Changes&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Organizational-Changes&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Organizational Changes&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Organizational Changes&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Finally, I want to address organizational changes that you may need to make.Â  Hopefully, you are already doing this.Â  But my experience tells me otherwise.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;Silos-Kill&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Silos-Kill&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Silos Kill&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Silos Kill&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Everywhere I go, QA is a separate department.Â  Why canâ€™t QA be co-located with the developers?Â  Wouldnâ€™t it make a lot more sense to have QA working with the developers to figure out a test plan so we can code for the plan rather than having the plan developed in isolation?Â  I get that exploratory testing might reveal additional issues, but certainly some of those issues can be revealed early by defining how the code is going to be explored.Â  Plus, making everyone part of the same team means they are all working toward the same goal.Â  No one gets offended that way.&lt;/p&gt;
