&lt;h2 id=&#34;Working-Backwards-from-a-Date&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Working-Backwards-from-a-Date&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Working Backwards from a Date&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Working Backwards from a Date&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is the most obvious, I think, so weâ€™ll get it out of the way first.Â  But it has some permutations that arenâ€™t quite so obvious that we need to examine as well.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, I get it.Â  There are some cases where there is a specific end date.Â  Something that is out of your control is happening on a specific date.Â  If you donâ€™t deliver the software by that time, then you might as well not create it.Â  But, in that case, you have to take the golden triangle into consideration.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;You can have it on a specific date.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;You can do it all.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;You can do it within budget.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unfortunately, even each of these have limitations.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;You might be able to release something on a specific date, but it may not be all that was intended.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Even if you could buy all of the resources you needed, which is hardly ever possible, there will be limitations to using all of the resources.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;If you have a limited budget, doing it all will probably suffer.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is where using Scrum has a huge advantage.Â  Because at least using Scrum, you are constantly picking the next most valuable feature to implement and each feature is released in a potentially deliverable state.Â  This is quite unlike the project Iâ€™m working on where components are being worked on that we canâ€™t even really test because they get called by something that has yet to be built.Â  Grant it, theyâ€™ll eventually be needed to have a viable product, but it is really hard to argue they are the NEXT most valuable feature when they canâ€™t even be tested.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, if you are working backward from a date, this could work if you add more resources, or you cut features.Â  Iâ€™ve worked in some organizations that were really good about figuring out what could be done and making sure the client was on board with the fact that we would only deliver that much.Â  But there have been other organizations where every time I suggested we not deliver a feature, Iâ€™ve been given a hundred reasons why that couldnâ€™t be done.Â  Needless to say, those projects are doomed.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Working backwards from a date is largely a management issue or a client issue.Â  But as they ask programmers for dates in light of the date, I find programmers are inclined to try to give numbers they think their managers want to hear rather than what they expect can really be done.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Going-with-Your-Gut&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Going-with-Your-Gut&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Going with Your Gut&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Going with Your Gut&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;The next most dangerous way of providing an estimate is to just go with your gut feel.Â  Hereâ€™s the thing about your gut.Â  Itâ€™s pretty optimistic.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I find that everything takes about twice as long as I think it will.Â  Iâ€™ve worked for some people who I quickly learned were only describing half of the project.Â  In those cases, Iâ€™d be off by a factor of four.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, Iâ€™ve learned to compensate.Â  Whenever Iâ€™m asked for a â€œrough estimateâ€ I always double whatever my gut thinks.Â  In some cases, Iâ€™ll pad even more.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But the right thing to do would be to spend a few hours and break the project down into task that take less than a day.Â  Ideally you want to break those tasks down into half day sized tasks.Â  Once you have all of the tasks spelled out, you can add up the hours and youâ€™ll have a pretty good idea of just how long the project will take you.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you are working in an office, donâ€™t forget to account for meetings, helping others, and other tasks that tend to happen over the course of a week when you provide the date you plan to be done.Â  Otherwise, youâ€™ll find youâ€™ll end up having gotten the hours right but still end up being late.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;How do you break the plan down?Â  What I do is I ask a very obvious questions.Â  Whatâ€™s the next thing I would need to do? Letâ€™s assume we are starting a new feature.Â  If you were to sit down and code that feature right now, what is the next thing youâ€™d have to do to code that feature?Â  It might be, â€œsetup the programming environmentâ€ or â€œsetup version controlâ€ or â€œget a test harness in placeâ€ or â€œcreate a branch from version controlâ€ it doesnâ€™t matter that it might take a half an hour to do.Â Â  Thatâ€™s actually good.Â  Just donâ€™t let it be so big of a task that it is going to take you several days to complete.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Next, assuming youâ€™ve done the tasks so far, what is the next thing youâ€™ll need to do.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You just keep doing this until you have a set of task that fit within the half day sized and all fully describe the steps you will take to get the project done.Â  While breaking task down this way will get you a much more accurate number, Iâ€™ve found that I still need to double the time I think it will take.Â  Especially if I know little or nothing about the project Iâ€™m getting in to.Â  The more you learn about the project, the less padding you should need to do.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Donâ€™t-Plan-for-the-Unknown&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Donâ€™t-Plan-for-the-Unknown&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Donâ€™t Plan for the Unknown&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Donâ€™t Plan for the Unknown&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;But in every project, there will still be some unknowns.Â  In fact, this past week, I hit one of those.Â  When I put it on my task list, I put it in as 8 hours figuring there would probably be some refactoring Iâ€™d need to do.Â  But when I got to it, what I found was that the refactoring project was a lot bigger than I had expected.&lt;/p&gt;
