&lt;p&gt;Before we really get started with the JavaScript stuff, make sure you have Java installed on your computer.Â  Youâ€™ll need that to run the Selenium stuff.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, to start out, install WebDriver.io First create a project directory for your new test project.Â  You can, of course, name it whatever you want.Â  Just make sure you make that directory your current working directory (CD into it.) Once youâ€™re in the project directory, create your package.json file by typing in npm init Which will ask you several questions about your project.Â  Answer the questions and&amp;#x2F;or accept the defaults.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Then install WebDriver.io by using the NPM command &lt;code&gt;npm install webdriverio --save-dev&lt;/code&gt; This should place wdio in your .&amp;#x2F;node_modules&amp;#x2F;.bin directory.Â  Run &lt;code&gt;./node_modules/.bin/wdio --help&lt;/code&gt; To verify that it is working.Â  If you are running on a Windows computer, youâ€™ll want to make those forward slashes back slashes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now that it is working, we are going to use it to configure a test runner file.Â  Type in .&amp;#x2F;node_module&amp;#x2F;.bin&amp;#x2F;wdio config One of the questions it is going to ask is which framework you want to use.Â  Pick â€˜Jasmineâ€™ Then it will ask if it should install the framework for you, pick â€˜Yesâ€™ Then it will ask where your tests are located.Â  Type in the correct location.&lt;/p&gt;
