&lt;h2 id=&#34;Page-Objects&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Page-Objects&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Page Objects&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Page Objects&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;So thatâ€™s the basics.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you are already familiar with writing Selenium testing, thatâ€™s the guts of what you need to know to get going.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you arenâ€™t, or youâ€™ve never heard of Page Objects, that is what I plan to cover next.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Generally, when we write our selenium test, we want to use a Page Object.Â  That is, we want to hide all of our Selenium specific stuff under an object so we can write our test without having to worry about the location of the elements on the screen changing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You see, hereâ€™s the problem you are going to run into.Â  You are going to write lots of tests.Â  At least I hope you do.Â  And then someday, you are going to want to change an ID of an element, or otherwise change how you find it.Â  If you write all of the tests so that they code directly to the Selenium code, youâ€™ll need to find every place you were looking for that element and replace it with the new lookup.Â  Not very DRY.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But, if you create a page object, youâ€™ll put your code there and call it from your tests.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So for an example.Â  Letâ€™s create a GooglePage definition.Â  Once again, because we are using Node 6.3 (or above) we can use the class keyword.Â  The browser variable is still available to us because it is global.&lt;/p&gt;
