&lt;p&gt;The problem of course is that there arenâ€™t a lot of browsers that support the LET keyword right now.Â  But there are transpilers that will convert your code from ES2015 to ES5.Â  And the way they do this is our final solution.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Solution-3&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#Solution-3&#34; class=&#34;headerlink&#34; title=&#34;Solution 3&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Solution 3&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;The problem with solution 1 is that while it works most of the time, it really isnâ€™t the most reliable way of solving the problem.Â  At the very least it sets up a lot more code that we really need.Â  If we peek under the hood to how the transpilers implement LET, what we see is that they take advantage of the fact that the CATCH block of the try&amp;#x2F;catch syntax has its own scope.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, all we have to do is throw i, catch it in the catch block and use the variable we caught in our callback function.&lt;/p&gt;
