&lt;p&gt;It tends to be a bit cleaner than solution 1 and is the solution I prefer. Â But, there is another strong reason for using this last solution that most people overlook. Â When you wrap a function with an IIFE like weâ€™ve done with solution 1, it changes the meaning inside the IIFE of &lt;code&gt;this&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;return&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;break&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;continue&lt;/code&gt;. Â Using the &lt;code&gt;try/catch&lt;/code&gt; mechanism allows you to treat the code as if it were inline with the code the &lt;code&gt;try/catch&lt;/code&gt; is in. Â This is probably closer to what you had in mind when you wrote the original code to begin with.&lt;/p&gt;
